                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary>No. 1: Oriental semi-cursive script; No. 2: Sephardic semi-cursive
                        script; No. 3: Sephardic semi-cursive script.</summary>
                     <handNote>No. 3: Colophon (on <locus>f. 15r</locus>) in cursive script. No. 3
                        was written by <persName key="person_7055">Mordecai Durant
                           Farissol</persName>
                        <foreign xml:lang="he">מרדכי דוראנט פריצול</foreign> for <persName
                           key="person_7056">Jacob Léon of Cavaillon</persName>
                        <foreign xml:lang="he">גאקוב/יקוב דקווליאן</foreign>, finishd on the 25th of
                        Av 5225=<date calendar="#Gregorian">1465</date>.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote><p>Nos. 1 and 2 are not decorated.</p>
                        <p>No. 3 contains several decorated rectangular initial word panels, which
                           have been outlined and painted using light washes of yellow and olive
                           green, with added details in red. The initial words themselves have also
                           been executed with red ink.</p>
                        <p>The design of the panels incorporates a mixture of abstract/geometric and
                           foliate motifs; foliate flourishes tend to issue outwards from the
                           corners of the panels. There are also a few figural elements, which are
                           either attached to the outsides of the panels, or placed near the panels
                           in the margins; these include a stork, a stylised human profile and a
                           lion.</p>
                        <p>It seems that the decoration has been executed by the patron of the
                           manuscript, <persName key="person_7056">Jacob Léon of
                              Cavaillon</persName>
                           <foreign xml:lang="he">גאקוב/יקוב דקווליאון</foreign>, since his
                           colophon/ownership inscription (<locus>f. 15r</locus>) has been written
                           around the drawing of the lion, clearly with the same red ink that was
                           used for the penwork decorations. The drawing of the lion, placed between
                           the words 'Jacob' <foreign xml:lang="he">יקוב</foreign> and 'of
                           Cavaillon' <foreign xml:lang="he">דקוליאון</foreign>, was therefore most
                           likely a visual pun on his by-name Léon.</p></decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <p>Dark green coated cloth over thin paper boards, quarter-bound in smooth
                        golden-brown leather. A black leather label bearing the gold-tooled
                        shelfmark near the base of the spine.</p>
                     <condition>Some repairs to the leather near the spine on the upper and lower
                        boards.</condition>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <accMat>The Hebrew items are bound together with many other fragments of various
                     sizes in Arabic, Latin, Syriac and English.</accMat>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate>No. 1: [15th cent.]; No. 2: [late 15th cent.]; No. 3: <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian">1465</date>.</origDate>
                     <origPlace>No. 1: [Orient]; No. 2: [Byzantium or southern Italy]; No. 3:
                        [Provence].</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>The patron and decorator of this manuscript, <persName
                        key="person_7056">Jacob Léon of Cavaillon</persName>
                     <foreign xml:lang="he">גאקוב/יקוב דקווליאון</foreign>, was the recipient of
                     another work, a treatise on the calendar by <persName>Moses Botarel Farissol</persName>, which was
                     also written in <date calendar="#Gregorian">1465</date> (see Henri Gross, <hi
                        rend="italic">Gallia Judaica</hi>, p. 539).</provenance>
                  <acquisition/>
               </history>
